<?xml version='1.0' encoding='UTF-8'?>
<ecoSpold xmlns="http://www.EcoInvent.org/EcoSpold02" xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" xsi:schemaLocation="http://www.EcoInvent.org/EcoSpold02 ../../schemas/datasets/EcoSpold02.xsd http://www.EcoInvent.org/UsedUserMasterData ../../schemas/datasets/EcoSpold02UserMasterData.xsd">
  <childActivityDataset>
    <activityDescription>
      <activity specialActivityType="1" id="4899efb4-24fa-53e8-9554-71fa3a35cc15" activityNameId="41ae5700-749e-4139-a2ce-aba344791645" parentActivityId="b1c80f8a-c3b3-4b84-b8b6-8c2eff55652f" inheritanceDepth="-1" type="1">
        <activityName xml:lang="en">market for flattened bamboo</activityName>
        <includedActivitiesStart xml:lang="en">This dataset starts with flattened bamboo leaving the gate of the producing entity, ready for distribution to consuming entities.</includedActivitiesStart>
        <includedActivitiesEnd xml:lang="en">The activity ends with the flattened bamboo being delivered to the consuming entity</includedActivitiesEnd>
        <generalComment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">This is a market activity. Each market represents the consumption mix of a product in a given geography, connecting suppliers with consumers of the same product in the same geographical area. Markets group the producers and also the imports of the product (if relevant) within the same geographical area. They also account for transport to the consumer and for the losses during that process, when relevant.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="1">This dataset represents the Ecuadorian market for flattened bamboo. Transport distances were estimated using the methodology presented in Zea Escamilla and Habert (2017).</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="2">Flattened bamboo is produced in a handcrafted process. The main application of flattened bamboo is in load-bearing wall systems, where it is used between bamboo poles to support the soil-cement mortar with which the walls are plastered (Murphy et al., 2004; Zea Escamilla et al., 2013). Flattened bamboo is also used to produce woven bamboo mats. </text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="3"></text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="4"></text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="5">References:</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="6">Murphy, R.J., Trujillo, D., Londoño, X., 2004. Life cycle assessment (LCA) of a Guadua</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="7">house. In: International Symposium of Bamboo e Guadua. Pereira, Colombia.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="8">Zea Escamilla, E. and G. Habert, Environmental impacts from the production of bamboo based construction materials representing the global production diversity. Journal of Cleaner Production, 2013.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="9"></text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="10"></text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="11">Zea Escamilla, E., Habert, G. Method and application of characterisation of life cycle impact data of construction materials using geographic information systems. Int J Life Cycle Assess 22, 1210–1219 (2017). https://doi.org/10.1007/s11367-016-1238-y</text>
        </generalComment>
      </activity>
      <classification classificationId="627be0b2-04e5-4179-b1eb-98755b9dda04">
        <classificationSystem xml:lang="en">ISIC rev.4 ecoinvent</classificationSystem>
        <classificationValue xml:lang="en">162:Manufacture of products of wood, cork, straw and plaiting materials</classificationValue>
      </classification>
      <geography geographyId="0d0e72a0-7d7e-11de-9ae2-0019e336be3a">
        <shortname xml:lang="en">EC</shortname>
        <comment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">transport distance is region specific </text>
        </comment>
      </geography>
